cs.NI, cs.DC, cs.IT, cs.SY, cs.PF 

Reasoning: 
1. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The paper discusses the design of crossbar switches, which are commonly used in networking and internet architecture. 
2. cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) - The paper proposes a parallel algorithm suite for crossbar scheduling, which falls under the domain of distributed and parallel computing. 
3. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper discusses the challenge of developing crossbar scheduling algorithms that can result in high switch throughput and low queueing delays, which is related to information theory. 
4. cs.SY (Systems and Control) - The paper proposes a system for crossbar scheduling in input-queued switches, which falls under the domain of systems and control. 
5. cs.PF (Performance) - The paper evaluates the performance of the proposed algorithm suite in terms of switch throughput and queueing delays.
